occurrences.line_text: And finding now fit opportunity
But finding no fit seat, the lifelesse corse it left.
And finding there fit solitary place
Finding no meanes how I might vs enlarge,
And finding in the way the scattred scarfe,
In stead of whom finding there ready prest
But comming to the place, and finding there
He her not finding, both them thus nigh dead did leaue.
He oft finds med'cine, who his griefe imparts;
Whom broad awake she finds, in troublous fit,
There him he finds all sencelesse and aghast,
He oft finds present helpe, who does his griefe impart.
Atin Cymochles finds.
Belphebe finds him almost dead,
Whom so she fittest finds to serue her lust,
And trampling the fine element, would fiercely rampe.
That no'te without an hound fine footing trace.
His idle humour with fine flattery,
No braunch, whereon a fine bird did not sit:
Stone more of valew, and more smooth and fine,
But onely womanish fine forgery,
Of her fine fingers, without fowle empeach,
And scorned parts were mingled with the fine,)
So diff'ring both in willes, agreed in fine:
Nor the fine nets, which oft we wouen see
Of such malengine and fine forgerie,
To finger the fine needle and nyce thread;
He fine would dight; sometimes the squirell wild
The same she tempred with fine Mercury,
Through fine abusion of that Briton mayd:
And secret feare, to see their fatall fine,
The which was framed all of siluer fine,
How euer finely she it faind to hide:
Thus finely did he his false nets dispred,
With golden foyle doth finely ouer spred
Saluagesse sans finesse, shewing secret wit.
Of euery finest fingers touch affrayd;
Of finest flowres, and with full busie care
To finger the fine needle and nyce thread;
Of her fine fingers, without fowle empeach,
Of euery finest fingers touch affrayd;
And with vnwearied fingers drawing out
And fingers filthie, with long nayles vnpared,
And cruell sword out of his fingers slacke
FINIS LIB. I.
Finis Book II.
FINIS
Well may she speede and fairely finish her intent.
To finish it: that so vntimely breach
Till they with mariage meet might finish that accord.
Vntill another tyde, that I it finish may.
To finish then, for other present hast.
That their broad flaggie finnes no fome did reare,
Least they their finnes should bruze, and surbate sore
Which with their finny oars the swelling sea did sheare.
Along the fomy waues driuing his finny droue.
That glorious fire it kindled in his hart,
Breedes dreadfull doubts: Oft fire is without smoke,
But full of fire and greedy hardiment,
Which when he saw, he burnt with gealous fire,
The fire of loue and ioy of cheualree
He burnt in fire, and gan eftsoones prepare
With fire not made to burne, but fairely for to shyne.
The shaking Palsey, and Saint Fraunces fire:
And slake the heauenly fire, that raged euermore.
That first the world with sword and fire warrayd;
And turning wrathfull fire to lustfull heat,
Conceiueth fire, the heauens it doth fill
And loue fresh coles vnto her fire did lay:
Whose harmefull head, thrice heated in the fire,
Yet sithens silence lesseneth not my fire,
And blow the fire, which them to ashes brent:
And hide the smoke, that did his fire display,
With fire and brimstone, which for euer shall remaine.
And brought vnto him swords, ropes, poison, fire,
With burning starres, and euerliuing fire,
He did receiue, whiles flashing fire about him shone.
With fire and sword the region to inuade;
That flames of fire he threw forth fro[m] his large nosethrill.
A flake of fire, that flashing in his beard,
With heat, toyle, wounds, armes, smart, & inward fire
With foule enfouldred smoake and flashing fire,
That glauncing fire out of the yron plaid;
To saue his bodie from the scorching fire,
Yet sparckling fire, and bad thereof take heed;
The housling fire did kindle and prouide,
And kindling fire at her faire burning eye,
In them the blinded god his lustfull fire
And pluckt him backe; who all on fire streightway,
Stared full wide, and threw forth sparkes of fire,
Wrath is a fire, and gealosie a weede,
The fire of sparkes, the weede of little seede,
A flaming fire in midst of bloudy field,
And round about him threw forth sparkling fire,
But added flame vnto his former fire,
To kindle his quencht fire, and thousand causes wrought.
Now brought to him a flaming fire brond,
That armd with fire, more hardly he mote him withsto[n]d.
Whereby close fire into his heart does creepe:
ther burnes in furious fire.
With wrathfull fire his courage kindled bright,
O how I burne with implacable fire,
And his whot fire burnes in mine entrails bright,
Or with the hidden fire too inly warmd.
His greedy flames, and kindled life-deuouring fire.
Their staring eyes sparckling with feruent fire,
Some rusty kniues, some staues in fire warmd.
It might breake out, and set the whole on fire,
For they of liuing fire most subtilly
Whereat they burning both with feruent fire,
Which seeth with secret fire eternally,
And then stole fire from heauen, to animate
Like as a fire, the which in hollow caue
Her fickle hart conceiued hasty fire,
Like sparkes of fire, which fall in sclender flex,
The outward sparkes of her in burning fire;
That from like inward fire that outward smoke had steemd.
And through her bones the false instilled fire
For no no vsuall fire, no vsuall rage
Most sacred fire, that burnest mightily
There shall a sparke of fire, which hath long-while
But in braue sprite it kindles goodly fire,
In whose faire eyes, like lamps of quenched fire,
And shortly grew into outrageous fire;
Broke into open fire and rage extreme,
To burne the same with vnquenchable fire,
For fire in earnest, ran with fearefull speed,
And saw the wicked fire so furiously
And left the fire; loue money ouercame:
A flaming fire, ymixt with smouldry smoke,
This fire be quencht by any wit or might,
Whom whenas Scudamour saw past the fire,
Armd with his thunderbolts and lightning fire,
And like a fire, when he Aegin' assayd:
And set it all on fire by force vnknowen,
Did priuily put coles vnto his secret fire.
Of flashing fire, and heare the ordenance thonder,
And fire did flash, like lightning after thunder,
Like sparke of fire that from the anduile glode.
And wrought in Lemno with vnquenched fire:
New matter added to his former fire;
Whose fire were better turn'd to other flame;
And beath'd in fire for steele to be in sted.
For euer when he burnt in lustfull fire,
And what he was, whose eyes did flame with fire;
By casting secret flakes of lustfull fire
Or raging fire of loue to woman kind,
Ran fierce at me, that fire glaunst from his horses hoofe.
Which in their spirits kindling zealous fire,
And fire deuoure the ayre, and hell them quight,
All flaming with their sacrifices fire,
In generation seeke to quench their inward fire.
So would he of the fire one ballaunce make,
Had worne the earth, so did the fire the aire;
That flakes of fire, bright as the sunny ray,
That all on fire ye would her surely weene.
To feeding of her priuate fire, which boyld
The holy fire, and all the embers strow
Against his Gods, and fire to them did threat,
That mote thy kindled courage set on fire,
And sparkling fire out of his furious eyne,
The beames whereof did kindle louely fire
His bloudy vessels wash, and holy fire prepare.
And by the twinkling of their sacred fire,
So for to quench his fire, he did it more augment.
In her right hand a firebrand she did tosse
Firebrand of hell first tynd in Phlegeton,
But now his courage being throughly fired,
At sight whereof his barbarous heart was fired,
With that fire-mouthed Dragon, horrible and bright?
To firends, to foes, which skill men call Ciuility.
And Cupid still emongst them kindled lustfull fires.
Together stroue, and kindled wrathfull fires:
In smithes fire-spitting forge, and nayles like clawes appeard.
That did presume his fathers firie wayne,
That from their shields forth flyeth firie light,
With firie zeale he burnt in courage bold,
To pluck it out with pincers firie whot,
Her firie eyes with furious sparkes did stare,
She sent at him one firie dart, whose hed
Is creasted all with lines of firie light,
Their firie Steedes with so vntamed forse
Yet harnessed his firie-footed teeme,
As when the firie-mouthed steeds, which drew
Through riuen cloudes and molten firmament;
Was all disperst out of the firmament,
And with her pineons cleaues the liquid firmament.
And tosse the deepes, and teare the firmament,
And left their scorched path yet in the firmament.
Being now placed in the firmament,
But firme is fixt, and sendeth light from farre
Her loue is firme, her care continuall,
No gate so strong, no locke so firme and fast,
And eke as pledges firme, right hands together ioynd.
Thereon an yron lock did fasten firme and strong.
Firme is thy faith, whom daunger neuer fro me drew.
Right firme & strong, though somewhat they declind;
On firme foundation of true bountihed;
Are not firme land, nor any certein wonne,
Then Merlin thus; Indeed the fates are firme,
But were for other causes firme and sound;
And with so firme affection were allyde,
For there no substance was so firme and hard,
But Artegall with constant firme intent,
No faith so firme, no trust can be so strong,
Firme Chastity, that spight ne blemish dare;
She held him fast, and firmely did vpbeare,
Thenceforth it firmely was established,
Both firmely armd for euery hard assay,
That had his furnitures not firmely tyde:
From thence, him firmely bound with faithfull band,
She firmely hath emprisoned for ay,
So firmely she had sealed vp her brest.
For sure a foole I do him firmely hold,
And euer firmely fixed did abide
And by the tailes together firmely bound,
But firmely following her first intent,
To whom his faith he firmely ment to hold,
Vpon his vsuall beast it firmely bound,
But firmely fixt they were, with dint of sword,
Of his true hart so firmely was engraued,
For breach of faith to her, which he had firmely plight.
But like a bulwarke, firmely did abyde;
Bynding himselfe most firmely to obay,
Vpon his card and compas firmes his eye,
Was firmest fixt in mine extremest case,
And Poets sage, the Firre that weepeth still,
They cannot finde that path, which first was showne,
Your first aduenture: many such I pray,
Your owne deare sake forst me at first to leaue
He in the first flowre of my freshest age,
First kindled in my brest, it was my lot
Of which the first, that all the rest did guyde,
Such one was Idlenesse, first of this company.
More old then Ioue, whom thou at first didst breede,
That first the world with sword and fire warrayd;
Yet first he cast by treatie, and by traynes,
His chaunged powres at first them selues not felt,
First made by him, mens wandring wayes to guyde,
If death it be, it is not the first wound,
For this young Prince, when first to armes he fell;
Him thought at first encounter to haue slaine,
When courage first does creepe in manly chest,
Then first the coale of kindly heat appeares
Feare to his first amazment, staring wide
Who first vs greets, and after faire areedes
The first of them that eldest was, and best,
The first and chiefest of the seuen, whose care
That from the first vnto the last degree,
At their first presence grew agrieued sore,
But first thou must a season fast and pray,
But hong still on the shield, as it at first was pight.
The tree of life, the crime of our first fathers fall.
From that first tree forth flowd, as from a well,
And in his first encounter, gaping wide,
From first to last in your late enterprise,
Layd first his filthy hands on virgin cleene,
Since errant armes to sew he first began;
And at his first arriuall, them began
The day that first doth lead the yeare around;
Eftsoones to court he cast t'auaunce his first degree.
Through fortune of his first aduenture faire,
The day that first of Priame she was seene,
When first I heard her horne sound with such ghastlinesse.
Approching, first the Hag did thrust away,
Must first begin, and well her amenage:
First her restraine from her reprochfull blame,
Therewith Sir Guyon left his first emprise,
To punish: yet it better first I thought,
To wreake my wrath on him, that first it wrought.
That was Pryene; she did first offend,
Who first to rayse our house to honour did begin.
When he in presence came, to Guyon first
Hard is his hap, that first fals in his ieopardie.
Him first saluted with a sturdy stroke;
And to her captiue sonne yield his first libertee.
And now is come to that same place, where first she weft.
That first did teach the cursed steele to bight
First got with guile, and then preseru'd with dread,
The antique world, in his first flowring youth,
The measure of her meane, and naturall first need.
In senselesse dreame; which sight at first him sore aghast.
The metall first he mixt with MedÃ¦wart,
First praise of knighthood is, foule outrage to deface.
Dyes not, when breath the bodie first doth leaue,
That sith I armes and knighthood first did plight,
Fiersly at first those knights they did assaile,
First she them led vp to the Castle wall,
Those two the first and last proportions are,
The first of them could things to come foresee:
For thy the first did in the forepart sit,
That of this lands first conquest did deuize,
And first taught men a woman to obay:
An happie man in his first dayes he was,
He with his victour sword first opened,
And taught her first how to be conquered;
Who him at first well vsed euery way;
Therefore he first wore crowne of gold for dignitie.
First Gorboman a man of vertuous life;
Nought else, but treason, from the first this la[n]d did foyle.
That first receiued Christianitie,
Was of the Britons first crownd Soueraine:
Then they which sought at first their helping hand,
It told, how first Prometheus did create
Quick, the first authour of all Elfin kind:
The first and eldest, which that scepter swayd,
Cleopolis foundation first of all:
The first troupe was a monstrous rablement
Snatcht first the one, and then the other Iade,
But freshly as at first, prepard himselfe to fight.
Giue ouer to effect his first intent,
How th'Earth his mother was, and first him bore;
First through the Euxine seas bore all the flowr of Greece.
Of th'Oceans fruitfull froth, did first appeare:
Doth first peepe forth with bashfull modestee,
Ne more doth flourish after first decay,
And shiuering speare in bloudie field first shooke,
They stayd not to auise, who first should bee,
First did it shew the bitter balefull stowre,
When first her tender hart was with his beautie smit.
The first of them by name Gardante hight,
And to her bed approching, first she prooued,
About their Lady first they flockt arownd,
Whereof did grow her first engraffed paine;
In liuing brests, ykindled first aboue,
But of their first intent gan make new dout
First entering, the dreadfull Mage there found
First rooting tooke; but what thing it mote bee,
First ill, and after ruled wickedly:
Carried her forward with her first intent:
Truth is his daughter; he her first did breed,
But to his first poursuit him forward still doth call.
First she him sought in Court, where most he vsed
Are fetcht: there is the first seminarie
Till thither they returne, where first they grew:
Which first was spoken by th'Almightie lord,
As it at first created was of yore.
All things from thence doe their first being fetch,
But well I weene, ye first desire to learne,
The first which then refused me (said hee)
But was as farre at last, as when I first begon.
To his first way. And as they forward went,
Gan first inquire of tydings farre abrode;
Nay let vs first (said Satyrane[)] entreat
In their first errour, and yet still anew
Both first and second Troy shall dare to equalise.
The Troian Brute did first that Citie found,
So huge a scope at first him seemed best,
That Albion had conquered first by warlike feat.
For sith the houre, that first he did them let
But euery Satyre first did giue a busse
From prosecuting of her first intent,
The first was Fancy, like a louely boy,
Reproch the first, Shame next, Repent behind:
Into the inner roome, from whence they first did rise.
Which first it opened; and bore all away.
In secret shade, and saw both first and last,
From her, to whom his fury first he ment,
Whom she requir'd, that first fayre Amoret
As plaine as at the first, when they were fresh and greene.
Now growen great, at first of little seedes,
For she at first was borne of hellish brood,
Firebrand of hell first tynd in Phlegeton,
Well know'st thou, whe[n] we friendship first did sweare,
And first laide on those Ladies thousand blames,
First he desir'd their cause of strife to see:
All three as one, the first hight Priamond,
Then entred Cambell first into the list,
As fresh as when it first was planted in the soyle.
First to her brother, whom she loued deare,
Then first of all forth came Sir Satyrane,
The wicked steele for mischiefe first ordained,
And with the first the hardy Satyrane
For from the first he to the last endured,
He at his first incomming, charg'd his spere
At him, that first appeared in his sight:
Him at the first encounter downe he smote,
When first he loued her with heart entire,
And afterwards did for her loues first hire,
There Florimell in her first ages flowre
But first was question made, which of those Knights
That Satyrane the first day best had donne:
For he last ended, hauing first begonne.
Then first Cambello brought vnto their view
Fie on the man, that did it first inuent,
First in the midst to set that fayrest Dame,
Vpon her first aduenture forth did ride,
That he which was the last, the first did farre exceede.
Yet is not this the first vnknightly part,
Let me this craue, sith first I was defyde,
That first I may that wrong to him requite:
So furiously she strooke in her first heat,
This mischiefe framd, for their first loues defeature,
He with his shamefull lust doth first deflowre,
For heauen, first author of my languishment,
Whose noble kind at first was sure of heauenly seed.
But firmely following her first intent,
My former hardnesse first I faire excusd;
Sith loue was first the ground of all her griefe,
First from one coast, till nought thereof be drie;
Who them with speaches milde gan first disswade
For from the first that I her loue profest,
For since the day that first with deadly wound
Flew first abroad, and all mens eares possest,
For oftentimes faint hearts at first espiall
As their Almightie maker first ordained,
First doe the merry birds, thy prety pages
So all the world by thee at first was made,
The first of them did seeme of ryper yeares,
Like to the Morne, when first her shyning face
First came great Neptune with his threeforkt mace,
First the Sea-gods, which to themselues doe clame
Did first proceed, then which none more vpright,
The first, the gentle Shure that making way
And comming to her sonne, gan first to scold,
And the first blossome of faire vertue bare,
From the first point of his appointed sourse,
For from the golden age, that first was named,
And men themselues, the which at first were framed
Is wandred farre from where it first was pight,
Shall find that from the point, where they first tooke
That since the time they first tooke the Sunnes hight,
Such first was Bacchus, that with furious might
There Iustice first her princely rule begonne.
Whom at the first he ghessed by his looke,
In euery thing, thou oughtest first to know,
For at the first they all created were
They turne to that, whereof they first were made?
First in one ballance set the true aside.
He did so first; and then the false he layd
So first the right he put into one scale;
And first of all issu'd Sir Marinell,
The first of them was hight Sir Orimont,
First he his beard did shaue, and fowly shent:
We on his first aduenture may him forward send.
To follow his aduentures first intent,
And though my land he first did winne away,
So Amidas, the land was yours first hight,
First she doth them of warlike armes despoile,
All arm'd to point, and first the Lists did enter:
She at the first encounter on him ran
From that first flaw him selfe right well defended.
For though that he first victorie obtayned,
I trust a liue, sith I thee fostred first;
Therewith she gan at first to change her mood,
His resolution was both first and last,
I will a while with his first folly beare,
But he at first or last was trapt in womens snare.
My heart at first betrayd, will ye betray
First rings his siluer Bell t'each sleepy wight,
But first the Tygre clawes thereon did lay;
That she to hunt the beast first tooke in hond;
Vppon his first aduenture, which him forth did call.
And rode him selfe vppon his first intent:
First, that sir Artegall should him array,
With his sharpe wheeles, in his first rages heat,
Into a Foxe himselfe he first did tourne;
First gan he tell, how this that seem'd so faire
First was a sage old Syre, that had to name
First there came Pittie, with full tender hart,
She first was bred, and borne of heauenly race;
Vp to the skies, whence first deriu'd it was,
In their first flowre, before this fatall teene
But on his first aduenture forward forth did ride.
To his first rage, and yeeld to his despight;
The which this Gyant reared first on hie,
She comming forth, when as she first beheld
Then to his first emprize his mind he lent,
On his first quest, the which him forth did call,
When first to Faery court he saw her wend,
But sure to me her faith she first did plight,
True is, that I at first was dubbed knight
That forst at first those knights backe to retyre:
And Enuie first, as she that first him eyde,
And Enuie first, as she that first him eyde,
Since it at first was by the Gods with paine
When Calidore thus first; Haile noblest Knight
But first him losde, and afterwards thus to him saide.
But by what meanes did they at first it reare,
Me first he tooke, vnhable to withstond;
Who hath not learnd him selfe first to subdew:
First, that ye better shall your selfe behaue
And then to his first quest he passed forth along.
To follow his first quest, when as he spyde
That first vnto his hand in chase did happen neare.
May witnesse well, did offer first to wrong,
But he me first, through pride and puissance strong
His wrath on him, that first occasion broke.
For since the day that armes I first did reare,
For first, next after life, he tendered her good.
But first him seemed fit, that wounded Knight
Since first he saw her, and did free from feare
Vnto his first exploite he did him selfe apply.
As fiercely yet, as when he first begonne,
His first assault full warily did ward,
Did taste the bloud, obaying natures first beheast.
The first of them by name was cald Despetto,
First learne your outward sences to refraine
The seede of all this euill first doth spring,
Which at the first before it had infected,
